Daimler, Hermes, Siemens, Volkswagen: Europe Equity Preview

-- B y   I n y o u n g   H w a n g
-- 
2011-06-10T04:00:05Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-09/daimler-hermes-siemens-volkswagen-europe-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index gained 1 percent to 271.76. The
Stoxx 50 Index jumped 1 percent to 2,541.82. The Euro Stoxx 50
Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, climbed 1 percent
to 2,778.12.  Credit Agricole SA (ACA)  : Citic Securities Co.,  China ’s
largest brokerage by market value, plans to acquire 19.9 percent
of Credit Agricole SA’s brokerage units, CLSA and Credit
Agricole Cheuvreux, for a total of $374 million. The shares fell
0.3 percent to 10.20 euros.  Daimler AG (DAI)  : The North American unit of the world’s
biggest truckmaker said it will hire an additional 1,400
employees. The stock gained 0.2 percent to 47.43 euros.  Hermes International (RMS)  SCA: LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis
Vuitton SA (MC FP), the world’s largest maker of  luxury goods ,
doesn’t intend to bid for Hermes, the bag maker in which it
holds a 20.2 percent stake, an LVMH spokesman said. Hermes
shares rose 2.2 percent to 191.95 euros, and LVMH gained 0.7
percent to 116.90 euros.  Siemens AG (SIE)  : German prosecutors arrested two
managers who had worked for Europe’s largest engineering company
in  Kuwait , on corruption allegations, and issued an arrest
warrant against a third, Financial Times Deutschland reported,
citing people in the justice sector without naming them. The
shares added 1.9 percent to 91.18 euros.  Tognum AG (TGM)  : The maker of industrial engines plans
to wind down its stationary fuel-cell development after Rolls-
Royce Holdings Plc decided it won’t take on the business,
Deutsche-Presse Agentur reported, citing a spokesman for the
company. Tognum shares increased 0.3 percent to 25.79 euros.  Volkswagen AG (VOW)  (VOW3 GY): Europe’s biggest carmaker plans to
appoint its general secretary, Wendelin Goebel, as head of
purchasing at the Audi luxury-car unit, Financial Times
Deutschland reported, without citing anyone. The stock jumped 3
percent to 127.50 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
